description.narrative: By 2023 state and non-state actors have strengthened capacity to implement programmes to increase equitable access to basic sanitation and hygiene for people at home, in schools, and health care facilities, in targeted UNICEF districts., which contributes to Children In Urban Settings / Local Governance, Cross-Sectoral Communication For Development, Sanitation, Sanitation (Covid). UNICEF aims to achieve this through Fostering Innovation And Use Of New Technologies, Harnessing Power Of Business And Markets, Operational Support To Programme Delivery, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: By 2023, underserved children equitably use safe water and practise safe sanitation and hygiene, including during humanitarian situations.

description.narrative: The COVID-19 pandemic has results in increased technical, material, and financial support to hand-hygiene, cleaning and disinfection for household, schools, and health care settings in Q1 and Q2 2020. Sanitation results have been achieved, and construction processes for WASH in schools and health care facilities taken forward with some delays. Going forward COVID related impacts on consumer sentiment and disposable household incomes resulting from forecast reductions in economic growth, and projected increases in consumer prices, are anticipated to be potential challenges that may adversely affect sanitation results achievement, where toilet adoption is mainly financed by household expenditure. | Status:Constrained | As-of Date:21/08/2020
